Vessels laden with over five million metric tons of goods berthed at the Lagos ports in the last one month. Lagos Port Complex (LPC) and the Tin Can Island port are the largest and busiest ports in the country.  The vessels, which regularly call at the Lagos ports include fishing, container ship, oil and chemical tanker, bulk carrier and offshore supply ship. Some the ships that visited the ports in the last one month included Desert Ranger, Desert Hope, Discoverer, Fairchem Thresher , Helan Equilibrium,  Yangtze Jewel, Talbot, Heroc, Hua Kong26, Merkur Ocean, Kwarine Azur, Nova Florida, V Tre, Ultimate, Queen Zenobia and Bow Pioneer. Others were Princess Erin, Princess Joanna, Heilan Brother, Yangtze Galaxy, Atlantis Alicante, Chayanee Naree, Karteria, Da Hong Xia, Chris Gr, Cl Biliu He, Bos Boutros, Green Maloy, Genco Picardy, RHL Comcordia , Seaspan Ningbo, Dredger Artevalde, Ranform Atlas ,Desert Glory and Cassiopea. The maximum length of the vessels recorded to have entered this port is 279 meters. The maximum draught is 13.6 meters.   - Advertisement - The maximum Deadweight is 113306t. Investigation by The Nation has showed that 49 ships had arrived in the Port within the last 24 hours. At the weekend, there were 103 vessels at the port while another 33 vessels were scheduled to make a port call at Lagos. Between May 28 and June 17, 2021, the Nigerian Ports Authority (NPA) said 24 ships laden with petroleum products, food items and others berthed at the port. This was made known by the agency in its publication, ‘Shipping Position‘. According to it, the ships arrived at the Lagos Port Complex.   The publication said that the ships contained bulk wheat, general cargo, frozen fish, container, trucks, bulk sugar, bulk salt, steel, pipes, petrol, gypsum, sodium sulphur, and butane gas.   NPA also reported that 14 other ships had arrived at the ports, waiting to berth with bulk malt, container, frozen fish, general cargo and chemical.     Soaring food prices to reach new heights this year     Govt can’t cut expenditure, says Akabueze     Explosion: No fears on Nigeria’s oil output   Also, the NPA said that 21 other ships were at the ports discharging bulk wheat, general cargo, base oil, container, frozen fish, bulk fertilizer, sodium carbonate, bags, bulk sugar, bulk gypsum, petrol and automobile gasoline.   Between November 25 and December 5 last year, the agency took delivery of 20 other vessels laden with petroleum products, food items and other goods.   Meanwhile, another six ships that had arrived the ports were waiting to berth with petrol, bulk wheat, bulk sugar and bulk fertilizer.   Nigeria Container Port Throughput was reported at 1,528,520.000 TEU in December 2020. This records an increase from the previous number of 1,484,000.000 TEU for December 2019.   Nigeria Container Port Throughput data is updated yearly, averaging 1,484,000.000 TEU from December 2008 to 2020, with 13 observations   The data reached an all-time high of 1,723,000.000 TEU in 2012 and a record low of 72,500.000 TEU in 2008   Nigeria Container Port Throughput data remains active status in CEIC and is reported by United Nations Conference on Trade and Development.   The data is categorised under World Trend Plus’s Association: Shipping and Port Sector – Table RP.UNCTAD.CPT: Container Port Throughput (CPT)   Expected ships in Lagos between February 9 and February 13 are             HB GOLDEN EAGLE Bulk Carrier  with 37720 metric tons;   AURIGA Refrigerated cargo ship  with 6088 metric tons;  STI PROVIDENCE Crude Oil Tanker with 74997 metric tons and LACTA Bulk Carrier           with 58713 metric tons.   The ships, findings revealed, were laden with bulk wheat, general cargo, frozen fish, container, trucks, bulk sugar, bulk salt, steel, pipes, petrol, gypsum, sodium sulphur, and butane gas.